re, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Berwickshire, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Stirlingshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1237–Aft 1304":"1237–after 1304","1237–1304":"1237–1304","1209–1278":"1209–1278","1250–1301":"1250–1301","1268–1305":"1268–1305","1270–1332":"1270–1332","1275–1375":"1275–1375","1215–Male":"1215–Deceased","1220–Female":"1220–Deceased","Aft 1304":"after 1304","1220":"1220","1275":"1275","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1305":"1305","1304":"1304","1237":"1237","1215":"1215","1268":"1268","1301":"1301","1278":"1278","1332":"1332","1375":"1375","about 1301":"about 1301","1209":"1209","Drymen, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Drymen, Stirlingshire, Scotland","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Berwickshire, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Stirlingshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mure","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Italian (Sicily): variant of   Morea  .","Scottish: variant of   Muir  .","English: occupational name from Old French <i>muer</i> ‘mewer’, i.e. someone who tended to hawks in the cages in which they were kept while moulting. Compare   Mew  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mura","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Japanese Akio, Hideo, Masao, Nanako, Tsutomu, Yoshi.  French Alphonse, Amie, Henri.","German: altered form of some similar (like-sounding) German or perhaps French surname. It is also common in France (Alsace), where it was first recorded in the form <i>Morrau</i>, later <i>Murra(w)</i>.","Italian (southern Sardinia): topographic name or nickname from Sardinian <i>mura</i> ‘mulberry’ or ‘blackberry’."]},{"name":"Muir","meanings":["Scottish: topographic name for someone who lived on a moor, from Older Scots <i>muir</i> ‘moor’ (an expanse of bare, wild upland country). There has been some confusion with   Mure  ."]},{"name":"Morea","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Saverio, Domenic, Ferdinando, Rocco.  Spanish Manuel, Carlos, Cesar, Elvira, Jesus, Mauricio.","Italian (Apulia): from the personal name <i>Morea</i>, originally a habitational name from Morea, the medieval name of the Greek region of Peloponnese, named as the land of mulberry trees, from <i>mōrea</i> ‘mulberry’.","Spanish and Catalan: habitational name from any of the places called Morea, in Badajoz, Navarre, and Lleida provinces."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sung, Jung, Yong, Chang, Kwang, Sang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jin, Kyung, Jong, Chong, Chung, Byung, Jeong, Pyong, Myong, Hak, Jin Hwan, Sook, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Lindsey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Lindsay  .","Irish: shortened and Anglicized form of various Gaelic surnames, as for example <b>Ó Loingsigh</b> (see   Lynch   1), <b>Mac Giolla Fhionntóg</b> (see   McClintock  ), and <b>Ó Fhloinn</b> (see   Flynn   and   Lynn  )."],"variants":[{"name":"McClintock","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Gille Fhionndaig</b> ‘son of the servant of (Saint) <i>Fionntóg</i>’, a personal name derived from a pet form of <i>fionn</i> ‘white’. Compare   Lindsey  .","History: A Scottish family of this name settled in Donegal in the late 16th century."]},{"name":"Lindsay","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Lindsey in Lincolnshire, England. This is first found in the form <i>Lindissi</i>, apparently a derivative of the British name of   Lincoln  . To this was later added the Old English element <i>ēg</i> ‘island’, since the place was virtually cut off by the surrounding fenland. The surname was taken to Scotland at an early date and is the name of an important and powerful Scottish family.","Irish: adopted as an equivalent ofvarious Gaelic names (see   Lindsey  )."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Mure of Lindsey was born in 1237, in Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, William de Lindsey, was 22 and her mother, Margaret Lindsey, was 17. She had at least 1 son with Malcolm Drummond 7th Thane of Lennox. She died after 1304, in Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1237–Aft 1304":"1237–pärast 1304","1237–1304":"1237–1304","1209–1278":"1209–1278","1250–1301":"1250–1301","1268–1305":"1268–1305","1270–1332":"1270–1332","1275–1375":"1275–1375","1215–Male":"1215–Surnud","1220–Female":"1220–Surnud","Aft 1304":"pärast 1304","1220":"1220","1275":"1275","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1305":"1305","13